{
    "id": "sysadmin/log-analysis",
    "title": "Inspect System Logs",
    "description": "Use journalctl and tail to extract incident evidence from Ubuntu services.",
    "image": "/assets/quests/linux_system_log_analysis.jpg",
    "npc": "/assets/npc/orion.jpg",
    "start": "start",
    "dialogue": [
        {
            "id": "start",
            "text": "Services leave breadcrumbs everywhere. Let's turn noisy logs into useful incident artifacts.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "journal-pass",
                    "text": "Start with journalctl"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "journal-pass",
            "text": "Export the last 200 lines for a critical unit using journalctl (for example: sudo journalctl -u ssh --no-pager -n 200 > journalctl-report.txt).",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "sysadmin-logs-export-journalctl-report",
                    "text": "Create journalctl report"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "tail-pass",
                    "text": "Journal report created"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "tail-pass",
            "text": "Now tail live logs into a concise incident summary (for example: tail -n 120 /var/log/syslog > incident-log-extract.txt).",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "sysadmin-logs-tail-incident-extract",
                    "text": "Capture incident log extract"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-1",
                    "text": "Incident extract complete"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quiz-1",
            "text": "What does journalctl -u nginx filter by?",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-2",
                    "text": "Entries from the nginx systemd unit"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-1",
                    "text": "Only kernel boot logs"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-1",
                    "text": "Only package install history"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quiz-2",
            "text": "Which command follows new log lines in real time from a file?",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-3",
                    "text": "tail -f /var/log/syslog"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-2",
                    "text": "ls -f /var/log/syslog"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-2",
                    "text": "who -f /var/log/syslog"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quiz-3",
            "text": "Why use --no-pager with journalctl during scripted analysis?",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-4",
                    "text": "To emit plain output without interactive paging"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-3",
                    "text": "To encrypt log lines"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-3",
                    "text": "To delete old logs"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quiz-4",
            "text": "What is a useful reason to tail only the last N lines before an incident review?",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-5",
                    "text": "It narrows focus to recent context and reduces noise"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-4",
                    "text": "It permanently compresses all logs"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-4",
                    "text": "It turns text logs into binary telemetry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quiz-5",
            "text": "After finding repeated auth failures in logs, what is the best next step?",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "finish",
                    "text": "Correlate timestamps, identify source IPs, and open an incident action plan"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-5",
                    "text": "Ignore it because the service is still online"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "retry-5",
                    "text": "Delete all logs immediately"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "retry-1",
            "text": "-u filters by service unit, which is key for targeted troubleshooting.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-1",
                    "text": "Retry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "retry-2",
            "text": "tail -f is the classic way to stream appended log lines.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-2",
                    "text": "Retry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "retry-3",
            "text": "--no-pager keeps journalctl script-friendly and easy to redirect to files.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-3",
                    "text": "Retry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "retry-4",
            "text": "Focused excerpts improve triage speed and reduce false leads.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-4",
                    "text": "Retry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "retry-5",
            "text": "Log evidence should trigger investigation and remediation, not silence.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "quiz-5",
                    "text": "Retry"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
